===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|linke|lang=en}} probably from {{etyl|non|en}} *{{term||hlenkr}}, from {{proto|Germanic|lang=en}}. Used in English since the 14th century.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[connection]] between [[place]]s, [[person]]s, [[event]]s, or [[thing]]s.
#: ''The mayor’s assistant serves as the '''link''' to the media.''
# One element of a [[chain]].
#: ''The third '''link''' of the silver chain needs to be resoldered.''
#: ''The weakest '''link'''.''
# {{computing}} The connection between [[bus]]ses or systems.
#: ''A by-N-'''link''' is composed of N lanes.''
# {{computing}} Shortened form of [[hyperlink]], especially one [[implement]]ed in [[HTML]].
#: ''The '''link''' on the page points to the sports scores.''
# {{mathematics}} A [[space]] [[comprise|comprising]] one or more [[disjoint]] [[knot]]s.
# {{Sussex}} a thin wild bank of land splitting two cultivated patches and often linking two hills.
#* '''2008''', Richard John King, ''A Handbook for Travellers in Kent and Sussex''
#*: They used formerly to live in caves or huts dug into the side of a bank or "'''link'''," and lined with heath or straw.

